{{Infobox venue | name = Judith Wright Centre of Contemporary Arts | nickname = The Judy | image = Judith Wright Centre of Contemporary Art.jpg | image_size = 300 | address = 420 Brunswick Street (corner Berwick Street), [[Fortitude Valley, Queensland|Fortitude Valley]] | location = [[Brisbane]], Queensland, Australia | coordinates = {{Coord|27|27|34.64|S|153|2|11.91|E|scale:195_type:landmark_region:AU|display=inline,title}} | type = Theatre | genre = music, contemporary dance, circus, cabaret, art exhibitions | built = originally Bushells Tea Company | opened = October 2001 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | construction_cost = | former_names = | seating_type = | seating_capacity = 300 | website = {{url|http://www.judithwrightcentre.com/}} }} The '''Judith Wright Centre of Contemporary Arts''' is a performing arts center in [[Fortitude Valley, Queensland|Fortitude Valley]] in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]]. The venue was renovated and re-opened as an arts centre in October 2001. The Centre is named after [[Judith Wright]], who was a celebrated Queensland poet<ref name="aq">{{cite web |url=http://www.arts.qld.gov.au/arts/judithwright.html |title=Judith Wright Centre |publisher=Arts Queensland |accessdate=6 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018011130/http://www.arts.qld.gov.au/arts/judithwright.html |archivedate=18 October 2013 |df= }}</ref> and an advocate for Indigenous rights and an environmental activist. Wright was one of two Australian poets considered for the Nobel Prize for Literature. She died June 25, 2000 in Canberra.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mcilroy|first=Jim|title=Judith Wright, 1915-2000|url=https://www.greenleft.org.au/node/22006|work=GLW issue 411, Wednesday, July 12, 2000|publisher=Green Left Weekly|accessdate=17 October 2013}}</ref>
The Centre is managed by the [[Government of Queensland|Queensland Government]] through Arts Queensland. Affectionately called The Judy, is located at corner Berwick Street and 420 Brunswick Street in [[Fortitude Valley, Queensland|Fortitude Valley]].
The venue includes performance spaces that are well equipped for lighting, sound and AV and the three rehearsal studios for dance, theatre and music feature natural light. The audience experience is intimate with a relaxed welcoming style of cabaret and racked seating. The main performance space is a black box style with plenty of flexibility to stage a diverse range of performances. Further info at <ref name="tau">{{cite book |title=Theatre Australia (un)limited: Australian Theatre Since the 1950s |last=Milne |first=Geoffrey |year=2004 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=9042009306 |pages=66–67 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCpEhrdarIMC |accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref> The venue encompasses to adjacent buildings, one two-story and the other five-story. The larger structure was originally a factory for [[Bushell's]] tea. Redevelopment of the site was designed by [[COX Architects & Planners]] and built by [[Brookfield Multiplex|Multiplex Constructions]].<ref name="cap">{{cite book |title=Cox Architects and Planners |last=Cox |first=Philip Sutton |year=2008 |publisher=Images Publishing |isbn=192074407X |page=297 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MTxGYgaNNPEC |accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref>
The Centre is home to some of Queensland's top arts and cultural organisations. Its facilities include a 300-seat performance space, rehearsal spaces for theatre, music, dance and circus, an art gallery, artist studios, coffee shop, bar and restaurant. It is home to a number of organisations including [[Australian Dance Council|Ausdance Queensland]], Carbon Media, contemporary circus [[Circa (contemporary circus)|Circa]],<ref name="aq"/> contemporary dance company [[Expressions Dance Company]],<ref name="aq"/> Flying Arts alliance Inc., The Institute of Modern Art,<ref name="aq"/> Qld branch of Matchbox Pictures and Ultra Linea Architects.
Each year, the venue hosts the [[Queensland Poetry Festival]].<ref name="qpf">{{Cite news |url=http://www2b.abc.net.au/EventCentral/View/Event.aspx?e=7134174&p=11 |title=Queensland Poetry Festival in August and the Poet in Residence program. |accessdate=6 October 2013 |date= |work=612 ABC Brisbane |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131008003548/http://www2b.abc.net.au/EventCentral/View/Event.aspx?e=7134174&p=11 |archivedate=8 October 2013 |df= }}</ref> The premier event for contemporary music BIGSOUND is held annually in September bringing together about 120 top emerging bands and national and international music buyers for a conference that attracts speakers including Peter Garrett, Nick Cave, Claire Bowdich and more.
